“FOUR SZNS”
37 ft 3.5 ft
Acrylic

Last mural of the year and it was quite a process to get this thing figured out. One long continuous stretch going from Winter to Autumn. The biggest hurdle was the spring section, melting snow was tough to depict going into a warm spring. 

Also added in some cryptid folklore from the Bridgewater triangle which is home to many unexplained phenomenas like Bigfoot, aliens, giant snakes and pterodactyls even put a yeti and the Loch Ness for good measure. Never seen any of them but the truth is out there.

Happy Holidays 🙌🏼

Haddonfield: Enter the Michael-verse
Acrylic on Canvas
40” x 70”

This piece took over a year to fully conceptualize, plan and finally paint. Had a half baked idea around January of last year.. imagine a piece where everywhere you look you see different Michael Myers. That thought resonated until I couldn’t ignore it any longer and bought the canvas. After months of figuring out the landscape, my jobs for the summer hit a fever pitch and was forced to let this simmer for the rest of the year.

Now, finally getting the time to finish it, this piece took a ton of effort to create the neighborhood from scratch, starting with the sky, horizon line, houses, road and then finally the characters. I tried to depict every Michael from all movies but I left out two, Halloween ends and the second Rob Zombie movie (since both were trash).

‘The Joe Rogan Mural Experience’
8’ x 20’
Acrylic

My mom bought me this shirt a couple years back, and now it’s on a mural. That’s what I call destiny.

I’ve been listening to Joe for over 4 years now and it’s crazy to see how much reach it’s gained on society. Feel like it hasn’t had the same charm since he moved to Texas but I still enjoy listening to an engaging guest once in a while.

My favorite time period was most certainly his LA studio, so that’s what I based this piece off of, also including some of his most notable guests.

Thanks @ronynazarian for the space and hope you enjoy 🙌🏼

“Lineage”
18’ x 11’
Acrylic

Had the opportunity to work with @jakeowilco & @gracienorcal to put this new piece up in Elk Grove (suburb of Sacramento) for the new Gracie Jiu-Jitsu school. Incorporating the lineage associated with the Gracie name I had to research where is started and where it is today to get the full scope. Just a note, not everyone from the family has been depicted.

Since it did originate in Japan, moved to Brazil and now up here in the US there were multiple steps that got the Gracie name where it is today.  Family of jiu jitsu masters and part originators of what we now call the UFC in the 90s they stay true to their heritage and are just as prolific as they were decades ago. 

Was a blast working up in north and getting a new piece solidified in a new area. After two months of travel I’m ready to get back down to LA and keep the train rolling.

Ending 2023 on positive hometown vibes.

“Weir Village”
35’ x 10’
Acrylic on wood

Had the pleasure of going back to my hometown Taunton MA and restoring an old mural that was painted back in 1999 by a local legend named John Barradas. After years of searching for someone to restore this piece, I caught wind of the project and reached out to the city.

Meeting new and reconnecting with some old friends, this was a piece to remember. Love when a community feels like they are being listened to and I’m glad I got to put my skills on display. Excited for 2024 and hopefully more projects to come around the country.
